@Francis Just because I was interested, since I also have never seen "nark" before, I looked it up. According to Wiktionary, "nark" original spelling of the word, perhaps deriving from Romani origin and cognate to "nose". 

The spelling "narc" for an informant is thought to be influenced by the unrelated word "narc" which is slang for a narcotics officer.

Google Ngrams shows that "nark" has been used fairly consistently since about 1750, while "narc" had a spike in popularity in the 70s and then a giant spike around 2005 to become much more common than "nark".

@Shrike

Interesting, Merriam lists the K variant for the noun form but notably does NOT include a K variant for the verb form of narc/narced.  Most sources show the verb only to mean annoy, not fink....

You may just be right.  :)

@SP
@and all the rest o' ya'

I have no opinion that I'm willing to express on narc/nark.  

Though I've tried to be a good speller, it does seem a bit meaningless to me to delineate correct vs. incorrect spelling when the two words are phonetically identical.

That is why, when I have an undiscovered error, I focus on vowels, which mimic each other all the time, at least to this untrained ear.  Then, failing that, check all the C's for K's and visa versa.  I've never had the 0(zero) vs O(letter) that others have mentioned.

Although once during solving I noticed a 0 where I meant O.  Gave my spine a bit of a chill because I'd convinced myself I was immune to that one.

@SP

Yes, that's my point.  The revealer lives towards the bottom and should come into play only as needed / as a surprise / as a reward.  Instead, this puzzle practically forces the player to confront the revealer before being able to enter top half answers.  It's poor form and no fun, at least for those of us who like to solve the grid in order.  Or, well, at least for me.  :)

If you're content to (or prefer to) jump all over the place when solving then it wouldn't be much of a bother.

@B I appreciate your perspective. It’s always good to hear why people like or dislike a puzzle and you describe your reasons very clearly.  

I enjoyed the puzzle and, as you supposed, I am content to jump around when solving a puzzle. I thought the visual of the crossed fingers was clever and I enjoyed using the reveal at 54A and 57A to unlock the NW.  I loved the twice in a lifetime clue at 38A.  The level of difficulty seemed a bit relaxed to me for a Wednesday, but I had a very full day today and it’s not done yet, so it was welcome.

I hope your next puzzle is more to your liking.

@Cindy

Very kindly put, thank you.  I like the idea of saving the revealer section for, well, a revelation later on, with the theme only slowly becoming apparent to me as I work through the upper half, but I can also see the possible appeal of jumping around, modern Jeopardy style, and really "working" the puzzle.

Someone recently theorized that constructors are purposely making the upper left quadrant the most difficult precisely to thwart/challenge us old fogies who like solving left-right up-down.  And I've noticed exactly that both here and in the LA Times... The upper lefts can be killers.  So flexibility might be called for....

